<paragraph id="354B36B45695FF20D1B7FC1BFEA6610B" blockId="137.[108,637,1017,1735]" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">
VOUCHER MATERIAL (TOTAL = 5): Jenaro 
<collectingRegion id="F730F8565695FF20D372FC18FF2F614D" country="Panama" name="Herrera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Herrera</collectingRegion>
(MUSM 5601, 5602, 23795, 23796), Quebrada Blanco (MUSM 21341); see table 60 for measurements.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="354B36B45695FF20D1B7FB9FFE2B61A8" blockId="137.[108,637,1017,1735]" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">
UNVOUCHERED OBSERVATIONS: We captured 12 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D1AFFB7DFEE761C9" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[148,336,1183,1206]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D1AFFB7DFEE761C9" box="[148,336,1183,1206]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Myotis nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at El Chino Village and another 3 at Tahuayo Farm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="354B36B45695FF20D1B7FB03FBB967F9" blockId="137.[108,637,1017,1735]" lastBlockId="137.[684,1213,226,1076]" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">
IDENTIFICATION: As traditionally recognized, 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D157FAE0FEA66066" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[108,273,1282,1305]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D157FAE0FEA66066" box="[108,273,1282,1305]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Myotis nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a species complex, from which Larsen et al. (2012), Moratelli et al. (2013, 2017), and Moratelli and Wilson (2014b) have recently described new species and elevated others from synonymy. Nevertheless, 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D06FFA65FE6F60E1" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[340,472,1415,1438]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D06FFA65FE6F60E1" box="[340,472,1415,1438]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">M. nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in its current, stricter sense) remains a widespread taxon, ranging from northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="4DE376245695FF20D000FA2AFE3F609F" box="[315,392,1480,1504]" name="Mexico" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry id="4DE376245695FF20D32FFA2AFDCA609F" box="[532,637,1480,1504]" name="Argentina" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and southern 
<collectingCountry id="4DE376245695FF20D03EFA0BFEF5637E" box="[261,322,1513,1537]" name="Brazil" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Moratelli et al., 2013, 2017; Moratelli and Wilson, 2014b). As now recognized, 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D157F9CEFF5B633C" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[108,236,1580,1603]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D157F9CEFF5B633C" box="[108,236,1580,1603]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">M. nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from other congeners by the following combination of traits: forearm &lt;
<quantity id="F20C9B515695FF20D358F9AEFF2D63FA" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" unit="mm" value="36.0">36 mm</quantity>
; dorsal pelage long, silky, and bicolored; no fringe of hairs along the trailing edge of the uropatagium; sagittal crest absent or weakly developed; and frontals steeply sloping (Moratelli et al., 2013). Descriptions and measurements of 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D52CFEE1FB0B6465" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[1047,1212,259,282]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D52CFEE1FB0B6465" box="[1047,1212,259,282]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Myotis nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been provided by Moratelli et al. (2013) and Moratelli and Wilson (2014b). Two subspecies are currently recognized: 
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D2A4FE85FBFE6401" box="[927,1097,359,382]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">M. n. extremus</emphasis>
(southern 
<collectingCountry id="4DE376245695FF20D397FE65FD4964E0" box="[684,766,391,415]" name="Mexico" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Mexico</collectingCountry>
) and 
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D271FE6AFC4D64E0" box="[842,1018,392,415]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">
M. n. 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D2A1FE6AFC4D64E0" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[922,1018,392,415]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">nigricans</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(eastern 
<collectingCountry id="4DE376245695FF20D557FE65FB0B64E0" box="[1132,1212,391,415]" name="Mexico" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Mexico</collectingCountry>
throughout tropical and subtropical South America on both sides of the Andes; Moratelli et al., 2013). However, analyses of cytochrome 
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D52FFE08FB96677D" box="[1044,1057,490,514]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">b</emphasis>
sequence data have discovered&gt;10 mitochondrial lineages within the range of the nominotypical subspecies (Larsen et al. 2012), highlighting the need for additional revisionary research on these bats.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="354B36B45695FF20D3F7FD72FB966611" blockId="137.[684,1213,226,1076]" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">
Ascorra et al. (1993) correctly identified their specimens from Jenaro 
<collectingRegion id="F730F8565695FF20D28DFD53FBB867B7" box="[950,1039,689,712]" country="Panama" name="Herrera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Herrera</collectingRegion>
. The additional voucher material we examined from the Yavarí- 
<collectingRegion id="F730F8565695FF20D397FD11FD4A6674" box="[684,765,755,779]" country="Peru" name="Ucayali" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Ucayali</collectingRegion>
interfluve conforms to previous descriptions of 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D229FCF6FC7D6654" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[786,970,788,811]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D229FCF6FC7D6654" box="[786,970,788,811]" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Myotis nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with measurements that fall within the range of size variation previously documented for the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7DEE653F5695FF20D3F7FC95FC54614B" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="354B36B45695FF20D3F7FC95FC54614B" blockId="137.[684,1213,226,1076]" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">
REMARKS: Of 
<specimenCount id="23F2FD3D5695FF20D256FC95FBB466F0" box="[877,1027,887,911]" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" type="generic">17 specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName id="F2F44D375695FF20D516FC9AFD6B66CF" baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis id="0780EAA65695FF20D516FC9AFD6B66CF" italics="true" pageId="137" pageNumber="137">Myotis nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
accompanied by ecological information from our region, 5 were captured in ground-level mistnets and 
<quantity id="F20C9B515695FF20D270FC38FC30668D" box="[843,903,986,1010]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" unit="in" value="12.0">12 in</quantity>
harp traps; these captures included 
<quantity id="F20C9B515695FF20D228FC19FC88616C" box="[787,831,1019,1043]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
secondary vegetation, 
<quantity id="F20C9B515695FF20D505FC19FBC0616C" box="[1086,1143,1019,1043]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="137" pageNumber="137" unit="in" value="12.0">12 in</quantity>
clearings, and 1 on a river beach.
</paragraph>
